**CORS errors mean the server didn't give your browser permission to read the response.**

Browser blocks cross-origin requests unless the server sends `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header.

**Common causes + fixes:**

| Cause | Fix |
|-------|-----|
| Server sends no CORS headers | Add `Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *` (or specific origin) to responses |
| Preflight `OPTIONS` request not handled | Server must respond 200 to `OPTIONS` with the CORS headers |
| Credentials + wildcard origin | Can't use `*` with `credentials: 'include'` — use exact origin |
| Wrong port (e.g. `:3000` → `:8080`) | Still cross-origin — add that port explicitly |
| HTTPS → HTTP request | Browser blocks mixed content before CORS even runs |

**Quick server-side fix (Express example):**
```js
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.header('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', 'https://yourfrontend.com');
  res.header('Access-Control-Allow-Headers', 'Content-Type, Authorization');
  if (req.method === 'OPTIONS') return res.sendStatus(200);
  next();
});
```

**If you don't control the server:** proxy requests through your own backend — browser never sees the cross-origin call.

Check the Network tab → failing request → Response Headers. If `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` is missing, the fix is server-side, not client-side.

